0d48

NOTES:

# transform the hexdump to binary
xxd -r -p PAD_hexdump > pad.bin

# after searching for tool that does that I found onetime
# encrypt using onetime
onetime -e -n -p pad.bin -o cyphertext plain_text 

# one time is cool but it adds additional meta info we don't want 
# so I just wrote a script to xor the plain_text and the pad
$ ruby xor.rb plain_text pad.bin ciphertext

# Note that xor is a simetrical operation so ruby xor.rb ciphertext pad.bin retreave_the_original_text
# will give you back the plain_text
# That's why one time pad is used only once (if the name isn't enough hint :D)!
